---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base title="gl1tch — your AI, your terminal, your rules">

<main>

<!-- ── Hero ──────────────────────────────────── -->
<section class="hero" id="hero">
<div class="wrap">
<div class="hero-inner">
  <h1 class="hero-title">gl1tch</h1>
  <p class="hero-tagline">your AI, your terminal, your rules</p>
  <p class="hero-desc">A composable CLI that chains shell commands and LLMs into workflows you own.</p>

  <div class="hero-install">
    <pre class="code copyable" data-copy="brew install 8op-org/tap/glitch"><span class="p">$</span> brew install 8op-org/tap/glitch</pre>
  </div>

  <a href="https://github.com/8op-org/gl1tch" class="btn btn-primary">View on GitHub</a>
  <a href="/docs/getting-started" class="btn" style="margin-left: 12px; border: 1px solid var(--border); color: var(--dim);">Read the docs</a>
</div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- ── Ask anything ─────────────────────────── -->
<section id="ask">
<div class="wrap">
  <h2>Ask anything</h2>
  <p class="section-copy">One command. gl1tch routes your question to the right workflow &mdash; PR URLs go to review, natural language gets matched by your local LLM.</p>

  <pre class="code"><span class="p">$</span> glitch ask "review PR github.com/org/repo/pull/42"
<span class="r">&rarr; routes to github-pr-review workflow</span>

<span class="p">$</span> glitch ask "what issues are open"
<span class="r">&rarr; routes to github-issues workflow</span>

<span class="p">$</span> glitch ask "CI status"
<span class="r">&rarr; routes to github-actions workflow</span></pre>

  <div class="feature-grid">
    <div class="feature-card">
      <h3>Smart routing</h3>
      <p>URL patterns detected instantly, freeform questions matched via Ollama.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <h3>Local-first</h3>
      <p>Your local LLM picks the workflow. Nothing leaves your machine unless you say so.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <h3>Zero config</h3>
      <p>Works out of the box with built-in workflows.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- ── Compose workflows ────────────────────── -->
<section id="workflows">
<div class="wrap">
  <h2>Compose workflows</h2>
  <p class="section-copy">Shell commands fetch the data. LLMs make sense of it. Chain them together in s-expressions.</p>

  <div class="split">
    <pre class="code"><span class="r">;; .glitch/workflows/github-pr-review.glitch</span>

(<span class="k">workflow</span> <span class="s">"github-pr-review"</span>

  (<span class="k">step</span> <span class="s">"fetch-pr"</span>
    (<span class="k">run</span> <span class="s">"gh pr view {'{{.input}}'} --json title,body,reviews"</span>))

  (<span class="k">step</span> <span class="s">"fetch-diff"</span>
    (<span class="k">run</span> <span class="s">"gh pr diff {'{{.input}}'}"</span>))

  (<span class="k">step</span> <span class="s">"review"</span>
    (<span class="k">llm</span>
      <span class="r">:provider</span> <span class="s">"claude"</span>
      <span class="r">:prompt</span> <span class="s">```
        PR: {'{{step "fetch-pr"}}'}
        Diff: {'{{step "fetch-diff"}}'}
        Review as a senior engineer.
        Flag bugs and security issues.
        ```</span>)))</pre>

    <ul class="callout-list">
      <li>
        <h3>Shell steps own data</h3>
        <p><code>gh</code>, <code>git</code>, <code>curl</code> &mdash; anything on your PATH.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h3>LLM steps own reasoning</h3>
        <p>Claude, Ollama &mdash; swap providers per step.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h3>Go templates</h3>
        <p>Chain outputs with <code>{'{{step "id"}}'}</code>, pass input with <code>{'{{.input}}'}</code>.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <h3>Your workflows, your repo</h3>
        <p>Drop .glitch files in <code>.glitch/workflows/</code> and they're live.</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- ── Extend with plugins ──────────────────── -->
<section id="plugins">
<div class="wrap">
  <h2>Extend with plugins</h2>
  <p class="section-copy">Any binary on your PATH named <code>glitch-*</code> becomes a command. No registry, no config, no approval process.</p>

  <pre class="code"><span class="p">$</span> glitch plugin list
  glitch-summarize
  glitch-deploy

<span class="p">$</span> glitch summarize README.md
<span class="r"># runs glitch-summarize, passes args through</span></pre>

  <div class="feature-grid">
    <div class="feature-card">
      <h3>Zero ceremony</h3>
      <p>Drop a binary on PATH and it's a command.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <h3>Any language</h3>
      <p>Go, Python, Bash, Rust &mdash; if it runs, it's a plugin.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="feature-card">
      <h3>First-class args</h3>
      <p>stdin / stdout / stderr pass through. Flags are yours.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
</section>

<!-- ── Real-world examples ──────────────────── -->
<section id="examples">
<div class="wrap">
  <h2>Real-world examples</h2>
  <p class="section-copy">These workflows are in production. Shell steps fetch live data, LLM steps make sense of it.</p>

  <div class="examples">

    <div class="example">
      <div class="example-header">
        <h3>Email triage</h3>
        <span class="example-tag">shell + jq + LLM</span>
      </div>
      <p class="example-desc">Fetch unread emails, filter out bots with jq, then ask an LLM which ones actually need a reply.</p>
      <pre class="code"><span class="k">name:</span> <span class="s">email-triage</span>
<span class="k">description:</span> <span class="s">surface emails that need a human reply</span>

<span class="k">steps:</span>
  - <span class="k">id:</span> <span class="s">fetch-unread</span>
    <span class="k">run:</span> <span class="s">|</span>
      gws gmail +triage --max 50 --format json \
        | jq '.messages'

  - <span class="k">id:</span> <span class="s">filter-bots</span>
    <span class="k">run:</span> <span class="s">|</span>
      cat &lt;&lt;'EOF' | jq '[.[] | select(
        (.from | test("noreply@|notifications@github|
          jira@|automation@|dependabot"; "i")) | not
      )]'
      {'{{step "fetch-unread"}}'}
      EOF

  - <span class="k">id:</span> <span class="s">triage</span>
    <span class="k">llm:</span>
      <span class="k">provider:</span> <span class="s">claude</span>
      <span class="k">model:</span> <span class="s">claude-haiku-4-5-20251001</span>
      <span class="k">prompt:</span> <span class="s">|</span>
        Classify which emails need attention.
        Skip newsletters, automated reports, mass CCs.
        Return JSON: [&#123;sender, subject, reason&#125;]

        Emails: {'{{step "filter-bots"}}'}</pre>
    </div>

    <div class="example">
      <div class="example-header">
        <h3>Task prioritizer</h3>
        <span class="example-tag">3 GraphQL fetches + jq scoring</span>
      </div>
      <p class="example-desc">Pull review requests, assigned issues, and your own PRs via GraphQL. Score them into HIGH / MEDIUM / LOW with pure jq — no LLM needed.</p>
      <pre class="code"><span class="k">name:</span> <span class="s">task-prioritizer</span>
<span class="k">description:</span> <span class="s">prioritized task list as JSON</span>

<span class="k">steps:</span>
  - <span class="k">id:</span> <span class="s">fetch-reviews</span>
    <span class="k">run:</span> <span class="s">|</span>
      gh api graphql -f query='&#123;
        search(query: "type:pr state:open review-requested:@me"
               type: ISSUE, first: 50) &#123;
          nodes &#123; ... on PullRequest &#123;
            number title url createdAt
            repository &#123; nameWithOwner &#125;
            author &#123; login &#125;
          &#125;&#125;
        &#125;
      &#125;' | jq '[.data.search.nodes[] | &#123;
        type: "review", number, title, url,
        repo: .repository.nameWithOwner,
        age_days: ((now - (.createdAt|fromdateiso8601)) / 86400 | floor)
      &#125;]'

  - <span class="k">id:</span> <span class="s">fetch-own-prs</span>
    <span class="k">run:</span> <span class="s">|</span>
      gh api graphql -f query='&#123;
        search(query: "type:pr state:open author:@me"
               type: ISSUE, first: 50) &#123;
          nodes &#123; ... on PullRequest &#123;
            number title url createdAt
            commits(last:1) &#123; nodes &#123; commit &#123;
              statusCheckRollup &#123; state &#125;
            &#125;&#125;&#125;
          &#125;&#125;
        &#125;
      &#125;' | jq '[.data.search.nodes[] | &#123;
        type: "own_pr", number, title, url,
        ci: (.commits.nodes[0].commit
              .statusCheckRollup.state // "UNKNOWN")
      &#125;]'

  - <span class="k">id:</span> <span class="s">prioritize</span>
    <span class="k">run:</span> <span class="s">|</span>
      jq -n --argjson r '{'{{step "fetch-reviews"}}'}' \
            --argjson p '{'{{step "fetch-own-prs"}}'}' '&#123;
        high: (
          [$r[] | select(.age_days > 2)] +
          [$p[] | select(.ci == "FAILURE")]
        ),
        medium: [$r[] | select(.age_days <= 2)],
        low:    [$p[] | select(.ci != "FAILURE")]
      &#125;'</pre>
    </div>

    <div class="example">
      <div class="example-header">
        <h3>Dashboard pipeline</h3>
        <span class="example-tag">8 workflows &rarr; static site</span>
      </div>
      <p class="example-desc">Run every workflow, dump JSON into an Astro data directory, build a static dashboard, open it. Whole thing takes 30 seconds.</p>
      <pre class="code"><span class="r">#!/bin/bash</span>
<span class="r"># One script orchestrates everything</span>

run_workflow() &#123;
  local name="$1" out="$2" fallback="$3"
  if glitch workflow run "$name" > "data/$out"; then
    echo "  $name... <span class="s">ok</span>"
  else
    echo "$fallback" > "data/$out"
    echo "  $name... <span class="k">fallback</span>"
  fi
&#125;

run_workflow email-triage     email.json    "[]"
run_workflow task-prioritizer tasks.json    '&#123;&#125;'
run_workflow review-dashboard reviews.json  "[]"
run_workflow my-prs           my-prs.json   "[]"
run_workflow ci-status        ci.json       "[]"
run_workflow calendar         calendar.json '&#123;&#125;'
run_workflow falling-behind   gaps.json     '&#123;&#125;'
run_workflow activity-log     activity.json '&#123;&#125;'

npx astro build &amp;&amp; open dist/index.html</pre>
      <p class="example-note">Each workflow owns its own data fetching and formatting. The build script just runs them and catches failures with sensible defaults. Swap any workflow without touching the others.</p>
    </div>

  </div>

  <div class="example-callout">
    <h3>You don't have to write the workflow</h3>
    <p>With the gl1tch skill installed in your coding agent, just describe what you want. The agent writes the workflow, saves it, and runs it.</p>
    <pre class="code"><span class="p">&gt;</span> build me a workflow that checks my open PRs across
  these repos, flags anything with failing CI, and
  gives me a prioritized list of what to look at first

<span class="r"># Your agent writes the workflow, saves it to</span>
<span class="r"># .glitch/workflows/pr-triage.glitch, and runs it.</span>
<span class="r"># Next time: glitch ask "triage my PRs"</span></pre>
  </div>

</div>
</section>

<!-- ── Give your agents gl1tch ──────────────── -->
<section id="agents">
<div class="wrap">
  <h2>Give your agents gl1tch</h2>
  <p class="section-copy">Install a skill and your AI coding agent can run gl1tch workflows directly in your project.</p>

  <div class="agent-cards">

    <div class="agent-card">
      <div class="agent-card-top">
        <div class="agent-card-label">Claude Code</div>
        <div class="agent-card-cmd">
          <pre class="code copyable" data-copy="npx @anthropic-ai/superpower install gl1tch"><span class="p">$</span> npx @anthropic-ai/superpower install gl1tch</pre>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="agent-card-note">Your agent gets glitch ask, workflow authoring, and pipeline execution as native skills.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="agent-card">
      <div class="agent-card-top">
        <div class="agent-card-label">Cursor / Copilot</div>
        <div class="agent-card-cmd">
          <pre class="code copyable" data-copy="curl -sLo .cursorrules https://raw.githubusercontent.com/8op-org/gl1tch/main/skills/cursor/.cursorrules"><span class="r"># Add .cursorrules to your project root</span>
<span class="p">$</span> curl -sLo .cursorrules <span class="s">https://raw.githubusercontent.com/
  8op-org/gl1tch/main/skills/cursor/.cursorrules</span></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="agent-card-note">Drops a .cursorrules file your agent picks up automatically.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="agent-card">
      <div class="agent-card-top">
        <div class="agent-card-label">Any agent</div>
        <div class="agent-card-cmd">
          <pre class="code copyable" data-copy="curl -sLo AGENTS.md https://raw.githubusercontent.com/8op-org/gl1tch/main/skills/generic/AGENTS.md"><span class="r"># Add AGENTS.md to your project root</span>
<span class="p">$</span> curl -sLo AGENTS.md <span class="s">https://raw.githubusercontent.com/
  8op-org/gl1tch/main/skills/generic/AGENTS.md</span></pre>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="agent-card-note">Generic instructions any LLM coding tool can follow.</div>
    </div>

  </div>

  <p class="bottom-note">Skills let your agent compose and run workflows without you typing a thing. Author once, delegate forever.</p>
</div>
</section>

</main>

</Base>
